## 5 Salt solutions

### Salt hydrolysis

When an acid and a base react, a salt is formed.

When salts dissolve in water, the ions are hydrated. **Hydration** occurs when the ions are attracted to surrounding water molecules through ion-dipole interactions.

Not all salts are neutral. There are certain salts, when dissolved in water, dissociate into ions which then _react_ with water to produce either acidic or alkaline solutions. This phenomenon is known as **salt hydrolysis**.

Salt hydrolysis is a _reversible reaction_. The pH of a salt solution can be predicted qualitatively by considering the ions of the salt that hydrolyse in water.

**(i)**: **Salt formed from Strong Acid (e.g. HC/) and Strong Base (e.g. NaOH)**: _Dissociation of salt_: NaCl(aq) Na^*(aq) + C_I_(aq) NaCl is a salt formed from a strong base, NaOH and strong acid, HC_I_. The Na^+ and C_I^- ions are merely hydrated, and will _not_ undergo hydrolysis. Hence, it gives a neutral solution.
**(ii)**: **Salt formed from Weak Acid (e.g. CH_3COOH) and Strong Base (e.g. NaOH)**: _Dissociation of salt_: CH_3COONNa(aq) + Na^*(aq) _Hydrolysis_: CH_3COO^(aq) + H_2O(I) = CH_3COOH(aq) + OH^(aq) CH_3COO^- is the _coniquate_ base of the weak acid, CH_3COOH, hence it behaves as a weak base in water and will undergo hydrolysis in water to liberate OH^- ions. As [OH^] > [H_3O^], pH of salt solution > 7 at 298 K (25 ^C).
**(iii)**: **Salt formed from Strong Acid (e.g. HC/) and Weak Base (e.g. NH_3)**: _Dissociation of salt_: NH_4C_I_(aq) + NH_4C_I_(aq) _Hydrolysis_: NH_4^*(aq) + H_2O(I) = NH_3(aq) + H_3O^(aq) NH_4^* is the conjugate acid of the weak base, NH_3, hence it behaves as a weak acid in water and will undergo hydrolysis in water to liberate H_3O^- ions. As [H_3O^-] > [OH^], pH of salt solution < 7 at 298 K (25 ^C).

