### Indicators

**(i) How do indicators work?**

An indicator is a substance that changes colour in response to pH changes of the solution it is added to. An indicator is a weak acid, whose acid form, HIn, has a different colour from its ionised form (conjugate base), In-.

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}\text{e.g.}&\text{HIn(aq)}&+&\text{H}_{2}\text{O(l)}& \Longleftrightarrow&\text{In-(aq)}&+&\text{H}_{3}\text{O}^{\text{+}}\text{(aq)}\\ &\text{weak acid}&&\text{conjugate base}\\ &\text{(colour A)}&&\text{colour B}\\ \end{array} \tag{1}\]

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}\text{The acid dissociation constant of an indicator is termed $K_{\text{in}}$:}&\\ &\text{similar to the idea of $K_{\text{in}}$}&\text{$K_{\text{in}}$}=\frac{[\text{In-}][ \text{H}_{3}\text{O}^{\text{+}}]}{[\text{HIn}]}&\text{and}&\text{pH}=\text{p} \text{$K_{\text{in}}$}+\text{log}_{10}\frac{[\text{In-}]}{[\text{HIn}]}\\ \end{array}\]

At different pH, the proportion of HIn to In- is different, giving rise to different colours.

In acidic solutions, [H3O+] is high. The position of equilibrium (1) shifts to the left, resulting in a large proportion of HIn.

In alkaline solutions, [H3O+] is very low. The position of equilibrium (1) shifts to the right, resulting in a large proportion of In-.

For the 2 colours to be distinguishable, one form must be about 10 times more concentrated than the other form, i.e. in the ratio 1:10. In general,

\[\begin{array}{ccccc}\text{If}&\frac{[\text{In-}]}{[\text{HIn}]}&=&0.1\text{, colour A is observed}&\Rightarrow&\text{pH}=\text{p}\text{$K_{\text{in}}$}-1\\ &\\ \text{If}&\frac{[\text{In-}]}{[\text{HIn}]}&=&10\text{, colour B is observed}&\Rightarrow&\text{pH}=\text{p}\text{$K_{\text{in}}$}+1\\ &\\ \text{If}&[\text{In-}][\text{HIn}],\text{ colour observed is a combination of A and B}&\Rightarrow&\text{pH}=\text{p}\text{$K_{\text{in}}$}\\ &\\ \end{array}\]

Hence, an indicator is found to change colour over an approximate pH range of \(\text{p}\text{$K_{\text{in}}$}\pm\text{1}\), which is called the working pH range of the indicator.

